<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-692-321  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 692 321.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 5 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Morris computer worm conviction appealed. (Robert Morris, Jr.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryComputer crimesComputer viruses.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (Cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MORRIS COMPUTER WORM CONVICTION APPEALED 12/05/90 NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A.,andO;1990 DEC 5 (NB) -- In arguments before the 2nd U.S.andP;  Court of Appeals, ThomasGuidoboni called for the overturning of the conviction of Robert Morris, Jr.andO;for unleashing a computer &quot;worm&quot; program in 1988 that affected thousands ofcomputer systems.andM;Guidoboni told Newsbytes that his arguments center on two points.andP;  &quot;There aretwo elements of every crime, the act itself and the mental element -- theintent of the person.andP;  Morris clearly did not intend damage and I feel thatthat is basis for overturning the conviction.andP;  Additionally, the law underwhich he was prosecuted is not a computer virus law and, in my judgement,does not cover the activities for which he was convicted.&quot;andM;Guidoboni added that the point of the applicability of the law could not havebeen made until the government had completed the presentation of its cases.andM;Morris, a former Cornell University student, was sentenced to three yearsprobation, 400 hours of community service and a $10,000 fine as a result ofhis conviction.andP;  The Court of Appeals has taken the arguments of Guidoboniand Justice Department attorney Ellen Metzer, who opposed the appeal, underadvisement and will reach a decision within the next few months.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19901205)</TEXT></DOC>